    {
      "type": "briefing-washing",
      "name": "Washing & Pollution",
      "limit": 1,
      "settings": [
        {
          "type": "header",
          "content": "Main Content"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "title",
          "label": "Title",
          "default": "Odor Drives Washing. Washing Drives Pollution. HercLeón Stops Both."
        },
        {
          "type": "richtext",
          "id": "content",
          "label": "Content",
          "default": "<p>Global textile research shows that 35% of ocean microplastics come directly from washing clothes, that detergent chemicals linger in rivers, lakes, and soil, and that the average washer–dryer setup produces hundreds of loads worth of carbon emissions every year. Dryers alone release over 120 million microfibers per household annually, and up to 90% of a garment's total carbon footprint comes not from manufacturing but from the repeated washing and drying people do at home. And because most clothes are washed every one to two wears, the environmental cost compounds endlessly.</p><p>HercLeón changes that entirely.</p><p>By preventing odor before it starts, our fibers reduce washing by up to 90%, which sharply cuts water usage, detergent runoff, electricity consumption, microfiber pollution, and overall carbon output. This isn't sustainable fashion marketing — it's a fundamentally different environmental model, one based on real behavior, real data, and real impact. Fewer washes mean fewer resources used and fewer microplastics released into the world.</p><p>That's why, when you follow the numbers to their natural conclusion, HercLeón is the most eco-friendly clothing in the world.</p>"
        } 
      ]
